{"title_page": "Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox International Football Competition\n| image          = Football, Athens 2004.png\n| size           = 150px\n| country        = Greece\n| dates          = 11\u201328 August\n| num_teams      = 16 (men) and 10 (women)\n| confederations = 6\n| venues         = 6\n| cities         = 6\n| champion_other = {{fbu|23|ARG}} (men)<br>{{fbw|USA}} (women)\n| second_other   = {{fbu|23|PAR|1990}} (men)<br>{{fbw|BRA}} (women)\n| third_other    = {{fbu|21|ITA}} (men)<br>{{fbw|GER}} (women)\n| fourth_other   = {{fbu|23|IRQ|2004}} (men)<br>{{fbw|SWE}} (women)\n| matches        = 52\n| goals          = 156\n| attendance     = 601052\n| prevseason     = [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000]]\n| nextseason     = [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008]]\n}}\n{{FootballAt2004SummerOlympics}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[image:footballlogo.jpg|left|]] -->\n\nThe [[Association football|football]] tournament at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] started on 11 August (two days before the opening ceremony), and ended on 28 August.\n\nThe tournaments take place every four years, in conjunction with the [[Summer Olympic Games]]. The associations affiliated to [[FIFA]] are invited to participate with their men's U-23 and women's representative teams.<ref>[http://fifa.com/documents/tournaments/olympic/Olympia_e.pdf Article 1 of the tournament regulations.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101200002/http://fifa.com/documents/tournaments/olympic/Olympia_e.pdf |date=1 November 2006 }}</ref> The [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|men's tournament]] allows up to three overage players to join the U-23 squads.\n\nThe [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|men's tournament]] was won by [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], coached by [[Marcelo Bielsa]], which held a record of having won every match without conceding a goal in the tournament. The Golden Boot was won by Argentina's [[Carlos Tevez]].  The [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|women's tournament]] was won by the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]].\n\n==Venues==\n*[[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]], [[Athens]]\n*[[Karaiskakis Stadium]], [[Athens]]\n*[[Pankritio Stadium]], [[Heraklion]]\n*[[Pampeloponnisiako Stadium]], [[Patras]]\n*[[Kaftanzoglio Stadium]], [[Thessaloniki]]\n*[[Panthessaliko Stadium]], [[Volos]]\n\n<center>\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n![[Athens]]\n!rowspan=12 colspan=2|{{Location map+ |Greece |float=right |width=700 |places=\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=38.036271 |long=23.787566 |label=[[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]]|position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=37.946447 |long=23.664317  |label=[[Karaiskakis Stadium]]|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=35.336667 |long=25.106111  |label=[[Pankritio Stadium]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=38.221806 |long=21.752189  |label=[[Pampeloponnisiako Stadium]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=40.625497 |long=22.967003  |label=[[Kaftanzoglio Stadium]] |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=39.387511 |long=22.931067 |label=[[Panthessaliko Stadium]] |position=bottom}}\n}}\n![[Patras]]\n|-\n|[[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]]\n|[[Pampeloponnisiako Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''71,030'''\n|Capacity: '''23,558'''\n|-\n|[[File:Olympic stadium,Athens 18.JPG|150px]]\n|[[File:Pampeloponisiako Olympic Stadium(1).jpg|150px]]\n|-\n![[Athens]]\n![[Thessaloniki]]\n|-\n|[[Karaiskakis Stadium]]\n|[[Kaftanzoglio Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''33,334'''\n|Capacity: '''27,770'''\n|-\n|[[File:Argentina Vs Italy 3-0 2004 Olympics Athens.jpg|150px]]\n|[[File:Kaftanzoglio west stand.jpg|150px]]\n|-\n![[Heraklion]]\n![[Volos]]\n|-\n|[[Pankritio Stadium]]\n|[[Panthessaliko Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''26,240'''\n|Capacity: '''22,700'''\n|-\n|[[File:Pagkritio.jpg|150px]]\n|[[File:Volos, Greece stadium at 2004 Olympic Games.jpg|150px]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Men==\n{{Main|Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament}}\n{{See also|Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team squads}}\n\n{|{{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|Men's football\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|ARG|2004 Summer}}<br/>[[Roberto Ayala]]<br/>[[Nicol\u00e1s Burdisso]]<br/>[[Wilfredo Caballero]]<br/>[[Fabricio Coloccini]]<br/>[[C\u00e9sar Delgado]]<br/>[[Andr\u00e9s D'Alessandro]]<br/>[[Leandro Fern\u00e1ndez (footballer, born 1983)|Leandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]<br/>[[Luciano Figueroa]]<br/>[[Kily Gonz\u00e1lez|Cristian 'Kily' Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br/>[[Lucho Gonz\u00e1lez|Luis Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br/>[[Mariano Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br/>[[Gabriel Heinze]]<br/>[[Germ\u00e1n Lux]]<br/>[[Javier Mascherano]]<br/>[[Nicol\u00e1s Medina]]<br/>[[Clemente Rodr\u00edguez]]<br/>[[Mauro Rosales]]<br/>[[Javier Saviola]]<br/>[[Carlos Tevez]]<br/>Coach: [[Marcelo Bielsa]]\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|PAR|2004 Summer}}<br/>[[Rodrigo Romero]]<br>[[Emilio Mart\u00ednez]]<br>[[Julio Manzur]]<br>[[Carlos Gamarra]]<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Devaca]]<br>[[Celso Esquivel]]<br>[[Pablo Gim\u00e9nez]]<br>[[Edgar Barreto]]<br>[[Fredy Barreiro]]<br>[[Diego Figueredo]]<br>[[Aureliano Torres]]<br>[[Pedro Ben\u00edtez (footballer, born 1981)|Pedro Ben\u00edtez]]<br>[[Julio C\u00e9sar Enciso (footballer, born 1974)|Julio C\u00e9sar Enciso]]<br>[[Julio Gonzalez (soccer)|Julio Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br>[[Ernesto Cristaldo]]<br>[[Osvaldo D\u00edaz]]<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Cardozo]]<br>[[Diego Barreto]]<br>Coach: [[Carlos Jara Saguier]]\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|ITA|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Marco Amelia]]<br>[[Andrea Barzagli]]<br>[[Daniele Bonera]]<br>[[Cesare Bovo]]<br>[[Giorgio Chiellini]]<br>[[Daniele De Rossi]]<br>[[Simone Del Nero]]<br>[[Marco Donadel]]<br>[[Matteo Ferrari]]<br>[[Andrea Gasbarroni]]<br>[[Alberto Gilardino]]<br>[[Emiliano Moretti]]<br>[[Giandomenico Mesto]]<br>[[Angelo Palombo]]<br>[[Ivan Pelizzoli]]<br>[[Giampiero Pinzi]]<br>[[Andrea Pirlo]]<br>[[Giuseppe Sculli]]<br>Coach: [[Claudio Gentile]]\n|}\n\n==Women==\n{{Main|Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament}}\n{{See also|Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's team squads}}\n\n{|{{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|Women's football\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|USA|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Briana Scurry]]<br>[[Heather Mitts]]<br>[[Christie Rampone]]<br>[[Cat Whitehill|Cat Reddick]]<br>[[Lindsay Tarpley]]<br>[[Brandi Chastain]]<br>[[Shannon Boxx]]<br>[[Angela Hucles]]<br>[[Mia Hamm]]<br>[[Aly Wagner]]<br>[[Julie Foudy]]<br>[[Cindy Parlow Cone|Cindy Parlow]]<br>[[Kristine Lilly]]<br>[[Joy Fawcett]]<br>[[Kate Markgraf]]<br>[[Abby Wambach]]<br>[[Heather O'Reilly]]<br>[[Kristin Luckenbill]]<br>Coach: [[April Heinrichs]]\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|BRA|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Andr\u00e9ia Suntaque|Andr\u00e9ia]]<br>[[Marlisa Wahlbrink|Maravilha]]<br>[[M\u00f4nica Ang\u00e9lica de Paula|M\u00f4nica]]<br>[[T\u00e2nia Maria Pereira Ribeiro|T\u00e2nia]]<br>[[Juliana Ribeiro Cabral|Juliana]]<br>[[Daniela Alves Lima|Daniela]]<br>[[Rosana dos Santos Augusto|Rosana]]<br>[[Renata Aparecida da Costa|Renata Costa]]<br>[[Aline Pellegrino|Aline]]<br>[[Formiga (footballer, born 1978)|Formiga]]<br>[[Elaine Estrela Moura|Elaine]]<br>[[Andr\u00e9ia dos Santos|Maycon]]<br>[[Delma Gon\u00e7alves|Pretinha]]<br>[[Marta (footballer)|Marta]]<br>[[Cristiane Rozeira de Souza Silva|Cristiane]]<br>[[Roseli de Belo|Roseli]]<br>[[Dayane de F\u00e1tima Rocha|Dayane]]<br>[[Grazielle Pinheiro Nascimento|Grazielle]]<br>Coach: [[Ren\u00ea Sim\u00f5es]]\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|GER|2004 Summer}}<br>[[Silke Rottenberg]]<br>[[Kerstin Stegemann]]<br>[[Kerstin Garefrekes]]<br>[[Steffi Jones]]<br>[[Sarah G\u00fcnther]]<br>[[Viola Odebrecht]]<br>[[Pia Wunderlich]]<br>[[Petra Wimbersky]]<br>[[Birgit Prinz]]<br>[[Renate Lingor]]<br>[[Martina M\u00fcller (footballer)|Martina M\u00fcller]]<br>[[Navina Omilade]]<br>[[Sandra Minnert]]<br>[[Isabell Bachor]]<br>[[Sonja Fuss]]<br>[[Conny Pohlers]]<br>[[Ariane Hingst]]<br>[[Nadine Angerer]]<br>Coach: [[Tina Theune-Meyer]]\n|}\n\n==FIFA Fair play award==\n\n===Women's tournament===\n*[[Japan women's national football team|Japan]]\n*[[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Association football at the 2004 Summer Olympics}}\n\n*[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/mensolympic/athens2004/index.html Olympic Football Tournaments Athens 2004 \u2013 Men], FIFA.com\n*[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/womensolympic/athens2004/index.html Olympic Football Tournaments Athens 2004 \u2013 Women], FIFA.com\n*[https://digital.la84.org/digital/api/collection/p17103coll8/id/57426/download Official result book \u2013 Football]\n\n{{EventsAt2004SummerOlympics}}\n{{Football at the Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[Category:Olympic football tournaments|2004]]\n[[Category:Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics| ]]\n[[Category:2004 in association football]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Greece|2004]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox International Football Competition\n| image          = Football, Athens 2004.png\n| size           = 150px\n| country        = Greece\n| dates          = 11\u201328 August\n| num_teams      = 16 (men) and 10 (women)\n| confederations = 6\n| venues         = 6\n| cities         = 6\n| champion_other = {{fbu|23|ARG}} (men)<br>{{fbw|USA}} (women)\n| second_other   = {{fbu|23|PAR|1990}} (men)<br>{{fbw|BRA}} (women)\n| third_other    = {{fbu|21|ITA}} (men)<br>{{fbw|GER}} (women)\n| fourth_other   = {{fbu|23|IRQ|2004}} (men)<br>{{fbw|SWE}} (women)\n| matches        = 52\n| goals          = 156\n| attendance     = 601052\n| prevseason     = [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000]]\n| nextseason     = [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008]]\n}}\n{{FootballAt2004SummerOlympics}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[image:footballlogo.jpg|left|]] -->\n\nThe [[Association football|football]] tournament at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] started on 11 August (two days before the opening ceremony), and ended on 28 August.\n\nThe tournaments take place every four years, in conjunction with the [[Summer Olympic Games]]. The associations affiliated to [[FIFA]] are invited to participate with their men's U-23 and women's representative teams.<ref>[http://fifa.com/documents/tournaments/olympic/Olympia_e.pdf Article 1 of the tournament regulations.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101200002/http://fifa.com/documents/tournaments/olympic/Olympia_e.pdf |date=1 November 2006 }}</ref> The [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|men's tournament]] allows up to three overage players to join the U-23 squads.\n\nThe [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|men's tournament]] was won by [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], coached by [[Marcelo Bielsa]], which held a record of having won every match without conceding a goal in the tournament. The Golden Boot was won by Argentina's [[Carlos Tevez]].  The [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|women's tournament]] was won by the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]].\n\n==Venues==\n*[[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]], [[Athens]]\n*[[Karaiskakis Stadium]], [[Athens]]\n*[[Pankritio Stadium]], [[Heraklion]]\n*[[Pampeloponnisiako Stadium]], [[Patras]]\n*[[Kaftanzoglio Stadium]], [[Thessaloniki]]\n*[[Panthessaliko Stadium]], [[Volos]]\n\n<center>\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n![[Athens]]\n!rowspan=12 colspan=2|{{Location map+ |Greece |float=right |width=700 |places=\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=38.036271 |long=23.787566 |label=[[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]]|position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=37.946447 |long=23.664317  |label=[[Karaiskakis Stadium]]|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=35.336667 |long=25.106111  |label=[[Pankritio Stadium]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=38.221806 |long=21.752189  |label=[[Pampeloponnisiako Stadium]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=40.625497 |long=22.967003  |label=[[Kaftanzoglio Stadium]] |position=top}}\n{{Location map~ |Greece |lat=39.387511 |long=22.931067 |label=[[Panthessaliko Stadium]] |position=bottom}}\n}}\n![[Patras]]\n|-\n|[[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]]\n|[[Pampeloponnisiako Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''71,030'''\n|Capacity: '''23,558'''\n|-\n|[[File:Olympic stadium,Athens 18.JPG|150px]]\n|[[File:Pampeloponisiako Olympic Stadium(1).jpg|150px]]\n|-\n![[Athens]]\n![[Thessaloniki]]\n|-\n|[[Karaiskakis Stadium]]\n|[[Kaftanzoglio Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''33,334'''\n|Capacity: '''27,770'''\n|-\n|[[File:Argentina Vs Italy 3-0 2004 Olympics Athens.jpg|150px]]\n|[[File:Kaftanzoglio west stand.jpg|150px]]\n|-\n![[Heraklion]]\n![[Volos]]\n|-\n|[[Pankritio Stadium]]\n|[[Panthessaliko Stadium]]\n|-\n|Capacity: '''26,240'''\n|Capacity: '''22,700'''\n|-\n|[[File:Pagkritio.jpg|150px]]\n|[[File:Volos, Greece stadium at 2004 Olympic Games.jpg|150px]]\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Men==\n{{Main|Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament}}\n{{See also|Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team squads}}\n\n{|{{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|Men's football\n|valign=top|{{flagIOCteam|ARG|2004 Summer}}<br/>[[Roberto Ayala]]<br/>[[Nicol\u00e1s Burdisso]]<br/>[[Wilfredo Caballero]]<br/>[[Fabricio Coloccini]]<br/>[[C\u00e9sar Delgado]]<br/>[[Andr\u00e9s D'Alessandro]]<br/>[[Leandro Fern\u00e1ndez (footballer, born 1983)|Leandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]<br/>[[Luciano Figueroa]]<br/>[[Kily Gonz\u00e1lez|Cristian 'Kily' Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br/>[[Lucho Gonz\u00e1lez|Luis Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br/>[[Mariano Gonz\u00e1lez]]<br/>[[Gabriel Heinze]]<br/>[[Germ\u00e1n Lux]]<br/>[[Javier Mascherano]]<