|France}} [[Daniel Moreira]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Yves Triantafyllos]]\n* {{flagicon|Senegal}} [[Diafra Sakho]]\n* {{flagicon|Zimbabwe}} [[Ovidy Karuru]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[N'Golo Kant\u00e9]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Lo\u00efc Damour]]\n\n== Managers ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em| \n* Blaud (1936\u201337)\n* [[Ernest Payne (footballer)|Ernest Payne]] (1937\u201338)\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Bourbotte]] (1950\u201356)\n* [[Jean Prouff]] (1956\u201358)\n* [[Roger Meerseman]] (1959\u201361)\n* [[Jean-Marie Pr\u00e9vost]] (1961\u201362)\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Cheuva]] (1962\u201366)\n* [[Angelo Grizzetti]] (1966\u201367)\n* [[Ernest Schultz]] (1967)\n* [[Jean Laune]] (1967\u201369)\n* [[Ramon Muller]] and [[Jean Aubert (footballer)|Jean Aubert]] (1969)\n* [[Daniel Langrand]] (1969\u201373)\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Pruvost]] (1973)\n* [[L\u00e9on Deladerri\u00e8re]] (1973)\n* [[Jacques Favre]] (1973\u201374)\n* [[C\u00e9lestin Oliver]] (1974\u201375)\n* [[Henri-G\u00e9rard Augustine]] (1975)\n* [[Daniel Langrand]] (1975\u201376)\n* [[Daniel Langrand]] and \"Doudou\" Douglas (1976\u201379)\n* \"Doudou\" Douglas (1979\u201382)\n* [[Bernard Soulliez]] (1982\u201386)\n* [[Gilbert Zoonekynd]] (1986\u201388)\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Bodji]] (1988\u201389)\n* [[Edmond Baraffe]] (1989\u201390)\n* [[Bernard Soulliez]] (1990\u201392)\n* [[Richard Ellena]] (1992\u201394)\n* [[Pascal Langlois]] (1994\u201396)\n* [[Bruno Dupuis]] (1996\u201397)\n* [[Alex Dupont]] (1997\u201398)\n* [[Robert Dewilder]] (1998\u201399)\n* [[Bruno Dupuis]] (1999\u201301)\n* [[Jacky Colinet]] (2001\u201303)\n* [[Pascal Langlois]] (2003)\n* [[Bobby Brown (footballer born 1953)|Bobby Brown]] (2003\u201304)\n* [[Bruno Dupuis]] (2004)\n* [[Philippe Montanier]] (2004\u201309)\n* [[Laurent Guyot]] (2009\u201310)\n* [[Michel Estevan]] (2010\u201311)\n* [[Pascal Plancque]] (2011\u201312)\n* [[Georges Tournay]] (2012\u201313)<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/players/trainers-fran-clubs.html#b France&nbsp;\u2013 Trainers of First and Second Division Clubs]</ref>\n* [[St\u00e9phane Le Mignan]] (2013\u201316)\n* [[Alain Pochat]] (2016\u201317)\n* [[Olivier Frapolli]] (2017\u201319)\n* [[Laurent Guyot]] (2019\u2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foot-national.com/foot-boulogne-laurent-guyot-nouvel-entraineur-off-118865.html|title=Boulogne : Laurent Guyot, nouvel entra\u00eeneur (off.)|publisher=foot-national.com|language=fr|date=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|US Boulogne}}\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.usbco.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Championnat National}}\n{{Championnat National 3 Group Hauts-de-France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boulogne}}\n[[Category:US Boulogne| ]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1898]]\n[[Category:1898 establishments in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{expand French|Union sportive Boulogne C\u00f4te d'Opale|date=August 2012|topic = sport}}\n{{Infobox football club |\n  clubname = Boulogne |\n  image    = [[Image:USBoulogne.svg|125px]] |\n  fullname = Union Sportive de Boulogne-sur-Mer C\u00f4te d'Opale  |\n  nickname = |\n  founded  = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1898}} |\n  ground   = [[Stade de la Lib\u00e9ration]],<br />[[Boulogne-sur-Mer]] |\n  capacity = 15,204 |\n  chairman = Jacques Wattez |\n  manager  = [[Laurent Guyot]] |\n  league       = [[Championnat National]] |\n  season       = [[2018\u201319 Championnat National|2018\u201319]] |\n  position     = 6th |\n  website  =  http://www.usbco.com/| pattern_la1=_boulogne1819h|pattern_b1=_boulogne1819h\n|pattern_ra1=_boulogne1819h| pattern_sh1=_boulogne1819h|leftarm1=000000|body1=000000|rightarm1=000000|shorts1=000000|socks1=000000\n| pattern_la2=_boulogne1819a|pattern_b2=_boulogne1819a|pattern_ra2=_boulogne1819a|leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n}}\n'''Union Sportive de Boulogne-sur-Mer C\u00f4te d'Opale''' (commonly referred to as '''US Boulogne''' or simply '''Boulogne''') is a [[Football in France|French association football]] club based in the [[Communes of France|commune]] of [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]]. The club was founded in 1898 and currently plays in [[Championnat National]], the third division of [[French football]], having been relegated from [[Ligue 2]] during the [[2011-12 Ligue 2|2011\u201312 season]].\n\nThe club was formed in 1898 and its achievements are minor with their biggest feat consisting of reaching the semi-finals during the 1936\u201337 edition of the [[Coupe de France]]. Boulogne play their home matches at the [[Stade de la Lib\u00e9ration]], which seats 15,004 having previously seated only 7,000 prior to its renovation in 2007.\n\n== History ==\nUS Boulogne were founded in December 1898 by a group of young athletes. While they mainly focussed originally on athletic events, they moved into the football industry and made a decent job in their first few years as a football club. Boulogne won the Maritime Championship three years running between 1904 and 1906. They next won the Championship in 1909 and their final victory of this division was in 1922. In 1924, Boulogne moved to the Northern Championship and fared well. The team also did well in the [[Coupe de France]]&nbsp;\u2013 reaching the quarter-finals in 1929 and the last 16 three times.\n\nIn 1926, Boulogne won the Northern League and only six years later, they became a professional club. In 1935, under chairman Marcel Lacroix, the team joined the professional leagues. However, they played averagely in Division Two but there were a few bright sparks in the team. The Coupe de France 1937 competition saw Boulogne make the semi-finals, but they were convincingly beaten by [[FC Sochaux]] 6\u20130. After the war, Boulogne reverted to amateur status&nbsp;\u2013 and only became a professional team again in 1957 when they were re-elected into Division Two. They stayed in Division Two for 22 years but plummeted through the divisions&nbsp;\u2013 suffering consecutive relegations. The Coupe de France competition only provided little respite, as the team made the last 16 three times.\n\nRobert Senechal arrived in 1983 and stabilised the club in Division Four. They missed out on promotion by a narrow margin in 1984&nbsp;\u2013 but were promoted in 1991. However, it was short-lived and they were relegated once again from whence they came. In June 1994, it was announced that Boulogne were in serious debt&nbsp;\u2013 owing  \u20a33&nbsp;million. However, mayor and billionaire John Muselet intervened to save the club and appointed Jacques Wattez as chairman. Under the leadership of Wattez, the club adopted a new name&nbsp;\u2013 Union Sportive Boulogne C\u00f4te d'Opale&nbsp;\u2013 in July 1994. The debts of the club were wiped and Boulogne&nbsp;\u2013 although still struggling in Division Four&nbsp;\u2013 reached the last sixteen of the Coupe de France again in 1997. They earned a home tie against Ligue 1 side [[Olympique de Marseille]]. Although, Boulogne battled their way through the match, they narrowly lost 1\u20130.\n\nBoulogne were slowly building their team in the [[Championnat National]] and under manager [[Philippe Montanier]], the club clinched promotion to [[Ligue 2]] with a tense 2\u20131 victory over [[SC Toulon]]. However, Boulogne were initially blocked from playing in Ligue 2 due to financial problems but after hard work, they were given the green light to play in that league for the [[Ligue 2 2007\u201308|2007\u20132008 season]]. They struggled that season and on the final day, they were occupying the final relegation spot, one point from safety. Boulogne played at home to [[Chamois Niortais FC]], who were one place above Boulogne. A tense game saw Boulogne win the match in the 95th minute through defender [[Damien Perrinelle]] and it kept Boulogne up whilst sending [[Chamois Niortais FC|Niort]] down to the Championnat National.\n\nThe [[Ligue 2 2008-09|2008\u201309 season]] saw Boulogne do the opposite from last season and win promotion on the final day of the season after beating [[SC Amiens]] 4\u20130, replacing Strasbourg in the final promotion place by a single point. Striker [[Gr\u00e9gory Thil]] finished top scorer with 18 goals as the side made their first ever appearance in the [[Ligue 1]].\n\n== Players ==\n\n=== Current squad ===\n{{updated|3 March 2020.|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usbco.com/equipe-pro-s17.html|title= Equipe pro |publisher=[[US Boulogne]] |language=fr|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/teams/france/union-sportive-de-boulogne-cote-dopale/2559/squad/|title=US Boulogne-sur-Mer C\u00f4te d'Opale Squad|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|nat=CMR|pos=GK|name=[[Guy N'dy Assemb\u00e9]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 2|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Noha Cadiou}}\n{{Fs player|no= 3|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=[[Anthony Scaramozzino]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Edouard Daillet}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|nat=GLP|natvar=local|pos=DF|name=[[M\u00e9ddy Lina]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 6|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Ma\u00ebl Illien}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=[[Evens Joseph]]|other=on loan from [[Stade Malherbe Caen|Caen]]}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Lenny L\u00e9onil}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=MAR|pos=FW|name=Said Idazza}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=CMR|pos=FW|name=[[Paul Garita]]|other=on loan from [[R. Charleroi S.C.|Charleroi]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Christian Senneville}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Youness Aouladzian|other=on loan from [[Stade de Reims|Reims]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=[[Guillaume Beghin]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=GUF|natvar=local|pos=GK|name=Simon Lugier}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=COD|pos=FW|name=[[Randal Kolo]]|other=on loan from [[FC Nantes|Nantes]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=R\u00e9mi Duterte}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=SEN|pos=DF|name=[[Jackson Mendy]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Mathieu Mion}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=C\u00e9dric Makutungu}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=MAR|pos=MF|name=[[Rayan Frikeche]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=27|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=[[Steve Shamal]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=28|nat=CIV|pos=MF|name=Badara Diomand\u00e9}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Ibrahima Traor\u00e9}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|nat=FRA|pos=GK|name=Raynald Framery}}\n{{Fs end}}\n<!-- This section is for current squad only. Any \"squad changes\" should go in the individual season articles where they exist -->\n<!--=== Out on loan ===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs end}}\n-->\n\n===Reserve squad===\n{{updated|28 March 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usbco.com/seniors-b-national-3-s162.html|title=SENIORS B - NATIONAL 3|publisher=US Boulogne|language=French|access-date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=SEN|pos=GK|name=Joseph Diatta}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Barthel\u00e9my Journ\u00e9e}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Bunyamin Kalkan}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Florian Latte}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Luc Heumel}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Marco Cato}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Sonny Duflos}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=DF|name=Timotey Deknuydt}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Adrien Lefebvre}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Amine Chmiti}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Antoine Rochoy}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Ibrahima Traor\u00e9}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Lucas Lemaitre}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Thibaut Navet}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=Nathan Vigneron}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=J\u00e9r\u00e9my Baret}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Julien Escouflaire}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Liam Libert}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Madiakher Niasse}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Noah Bongo}}\n{{Fs player|no=\u2014|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=Phayel Charaf}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Other Staff===\n\n* Manager : {{flagicon|France}} Olivier Frapolli\n* Assistant : {{flagicon|France}} Alexis Loreille\n* Physical : {{flagicon|France}} Michael Sirvent\n* Goalkeeping Coach : {{flagicon|France}} [[Franck Grandel]]\n* Technical Director : {{flagicon|France}} [[Aur\u00e9lien Capoue]]\n* Scouting : {{flagicon|France}} Lo\u00efc Salvadori\n\n=== Notable players ===\nBelow are the notable players who have represented Boulogne in [[Ligue 1|league]] and international competition since the club's foundation in 1919.\n\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Franck Rib\u00e9ry]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Lucien Leduc]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Daniel Moreira]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} {{flagicon|Greece}} [[Yves Triantafyllos]]\n* {{flagicon|Senegal}} [[Diafra Sakho]]\n* {{flagicon|Zimbabwe}} [[Ovidy Karuru]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[N'Golo Kant\u00e9]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Lo\u00efc Damour]]\n{{EngvarB|date = May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = May 2014}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n== Managers ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em| \n* Blaud (1936\u201337)\n* [[Ernest Payne (footballer)|Ernest Payne]] (1937\u201338)\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Bourbotte]] (1950\u201356)\n* [[Jean Prouff]] (1956\u201358)\n* [[Roger Meerseman]] (1959\u201361)\n* [[Jean-Marie Pr\u00e9vost]] (1961\u201362)\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Cheuva]] (1962\u201366)\n* [[Angelo Grizzetti]] (1966\u201367)\n* [[Ernest Schultz]] (1967)\n* [[Jean Laune]] (1967\u201369)\n* [[Ramon Muller]] and [[Jean Aubert (footballer)|Jean Aubert]] (1969)\n* [[Daniel Langrand]] (1969\u201373)\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Pruvost]] (1973)\n* [[L\u00e9on Deladerri\u00e8re]] (1973)\n* [[Jacques Favre]] (1973\u201374)\n* [[C\u00e9lestin Oliver]] (1974\u201375)\n* [[Henri-G\u00e9rard Augustine]] (1975)\n* [[Daniel Langrand]] (1975\u201376)\n* [[Daniel Langrand]] and \"Doudou\" Douglas (1976